Championing a data-driven culture
1. Identify key stakeholders
• Ie business leaders, IT, data analysts, end-users

To champion a data-driven culture, the first steps is to identify the people who create, manage, analyse, and use data across the organisation.

The key stakeholders include -

Business leaders and Senior management - Sets the overall direction, approves investment and to encourage teams in using data whilst making decisions.

IT & System teams - Maintain the systems, databases, security, and infrastructure needed to collect and access reliable data.

Data analysts and data engineers – Prepare, validate, analyse, and to present data so that it can be understood and used effectively.

Department managers - Translate objectives into measurable targets and by ensuring data is used within their teams.

End Users - To use reports, dashboards, spreadsheets and operational systems in their day-to-day roles.

Data Owners and data stewards - Take responsibility for the accuracy, quality and the appropriate use of specific datasets.

External stakeholders – Suppliers, customers, developers, or service providers provide data or rely on information that is produced by the organisation.

At Co-ordSport, this could include senior managemenent, the data and IT teams, purchasing, sales, marketing, warehouse staff, customer service.
web developers, and employees who uses MAM Autopart, Phocas, website reports.

Involving those groups help to ensure that data initiatives addresses genuine business needs rather than being developed in isolation.

2. Analyse effective stakeholder collaboration strategies

Effective stakeholder collaboration is essential whilst promoting a data-driven culture because different departments have different priorities, 
responsibilities, and levels of data knowledge. Collaboration ensure that data initiatives are practical, supported by the business, and is capable of 
delivering measurable value.

• Align data initiatives with business objectives

Data initiatives should be directly linked to the organisation's wider business objectives. Rather than collecting or analysing data without a clear
purpose, stakeholders should agree on the specific business problems that the initative is intended to solve.

For example, at Co-ordSport, a data initiative might support objectives such as:

• Improving the accuracy and completeness of product information
• Reducing the time required to upload supplier data
• Increasing website sales and conversion rates
• To improve stock availability and purchasing decisions
• Reduce duplicate products, incorrect fitment data, and website errors
• To give sales and management teams fast access to reliable reports

Business leaders should define the strategic goals, while data analysts, IT Teams, department managers, and end-users help determine what data is required and how
it should be presented. This collaborative approach ensure that technical work supports genuine operational needs.

For example, when developing a new product database to replace existing systems, senior management might focus on cost savings and efficiency. The data team
may focus on data quality, validation, and structure, while sales and purchasing teams might require quick access to product descriptions, prices, stock-take,
images, and vehicle applications. Bringing these requirements together helps ensure that the final system benefits the whole organisation.

Stakeholder collaboration can be supported through regular meetings, progress updates, demonstrations, feedback sessions, and clearly assigned
resonsibilities. Communication should be adapted to the stakeholders. Senior management may require a summary of costs, risks, and expected
benefits, where as technical teams might require detailed specifications, data mappings, and validation rules.


• Stakeholder engagement plan

A stakeholder enagement plan should document how each stakeholder would be involved throughout the data initiative. This should include their roles, level
of influence, information requirements, communication methods, frequency of communication and responsibilities.

Stakeholder - Senior Management
Interest or Responsibility - Business objectives, costs, risks, and return of investment
Influence - High
Engagement Method - Progress reports, review meetings and project summaries
Communication Frequency - Monthly or at key milestones

Stakeholder - Data Team
Interest or Responsibility - Data collection, cleansing, validation, analysis and reporting
Influence - High
Engagement Method - Working meetings, shared documents and task tracking
Communication Frequency - Daily or weekly

Stakeholder - IT & Developers
Interest or Responsibility - Systems, databases, integrations, access and security
Influence - High
Engagement Method - Technical meetings, specifications, and testing sessions
Communication Frequency - Weekly

Stakeholder - Department managers
Interest or Responsibility - Operational requirements and team performance
Influence - Medium to High
Engagement Method - Workshops, meetings, and dashboard reviews
Communication Frequency - Fortnightly or monthly

Stakeholder - Sales and purchasing teams
Interest or Responsibility - Product, pricing, supplier and stock information
Influence - High
Engagement Method - Feedback sessions, system demonstrations and user testing
Communication Frequency - At key development stages

Stakeholder - Marketing and ecommerce teams
Interest or Responsibility - Website data, SEO, product content and customer engagement
Influence - Medium
Engagement Method - Meetings, reports and shared data reviews
Communication Frequency - Weekly or fortnightly

Stakeholder - End-users
Interest or Responsibility - Usability, accuracy and practical day-to-day requirements
Influence - Medium
Enagement Method - Surveys, interviews, demonstrations and user acceptance testing
Communication Frequency - During design & testing

Stakeholder - External suppliers or service providers
Interest or Responsiblity - Data feeds, system support and technical requirements
Influence - Medium
Enagement Method - Emails, specification documents & project meetings
Communication Frequency - As required
